author: Martens, Michael
notes: This is Kantewu (Central) dialect Uma. Other Uma dialects are Southern, Toleeʔ, Tobaku, and Winatu-Toriʔuntu.
problems: I will use ʔ for glottal stop; β for bilabial fricative; č for alveo-palatal affricate (always prenasalized); j for voiced alveo-palatal affricate (i.e., like English j); ŋ for velar nasal; ñ for alveo-palatal nasal.

author: to breathe
glottocode: mo-  prefix; perhaps the root contains a frozen  -in- infix

author: person/human being
glottocode: root is tau; 3rd sg possessive -na is almost always used with it

author: husband
glottocode: same as 'man' but a possessive pronoun is used if it means husband

author: wife
glottocode: same as 'woman' but a possessive is used if it means wife

author: to tie up, fasten
glottocode: mpo- prefix. Note: there are MANY terms for tying; this is the most common response and is somewhat generic.

author: to hunt
glottocode: mo- prefix on archaic term for 'dog'

author: to shoot
glottocode: bow and arrow not used; but the term panaʔ is used of hurling something (rock, stick), and the term saku is used of hurling a spear

author: to stab, pierce
glottocode: stab with pointy object like awl, needle

author: to hit
glottocode: There are several terms for hitting; this is the most common.

author: stick/wood
glottocode: No term for 'stick'; kaju = wood/tree; raʔa = branch

author: to plant
glottocode: to plant a seed or seedling

author: to plant
glottocode: to plant seeds using a dibble stick

author: dog
glottocode: Obsolete form (ahu) still used as verb to hunt; cf. 69.

author: fat/grease
glottocode: layer of fat under skin (especially of pigs)

author: fish
glottocode: meat in general but often used for fish

author: to blow
glottocode: blow (with the mouth) on a fire

author: thick
glottocode: precise term for 'thick' but rarely used.

author: good
glottocode: Tolee', Winatu-Toriʔuntu dialects: beloʔ (of which lompeʔ is an irregular metathesis)
